        <ANNOTATION>
            <ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION ANNOTATION_ID="a1"
                TIME_SLOT_REF1="ts1" TIME_SLOT_REF2="ts2">
                <ANNOTATION_VALUE>this is katerina heidhausen executive editor of harrison’s principles of internal medicine</ANNOTATION_VALUE>
            </ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION>
        </ANNOTATION>
        <ANNOTATION>
            <ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION ANNOTATION_ID="a2"
                TIME_SLOT_REF1="ts3" TIME_SLOT_REF2="ts4">
                <ANNOTATION_VALUE>harrison’s podclass is brought to you by mcgraw hill’s accessmedicine the online medical resource that delivers the latest content from the best minds in medicine and now on to that episode</ANNOTATION_VALUE>
            </ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION>
        </ANNOTATION>
        <ANNOTATION>
            <ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION ANNOTATION_ID="a3"
                TIME_SLOT_REF1="ts5" TIME_SLOT_REF2="ts6">
                <ANNOTATION_VALUE>hi everyone welcome back to harrison’s podclass we’re your cohosts i’m doctor cathy handy</ANNOTATION_VALUE>
            </ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION>
        </ANNOTATION>
        <ANNOTATION>
            <ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION ANNOTATION_ID="a4"
                TIME_SLOT_REF1="ts7" TIME_SLOT_REF2="ts8">
                <ANNOTATION_VALUE>and i’m doctor charlie wiener and we’re joining you from the johns hopkins school of medicine</ANNOTATION_VALUE>
            </ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION>
        </ANNOTATION>
        <ANNOTATION>
            <ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION ANNOTATION_ID="a5"
                TIME_SLOT_REF1="ts9" TIME_SLOT_REF2="ts10">
                <ANNOTATION_VALUE>welcome to harrison’s podclass today’s patient is a thirty-eight-year-old with fever hypotension and confusion</ANNOTATION_VALUE>
            </ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION>
        </ANNOTATION>
        <ANNOTATION>
            <ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION ANNOTATION_ID="a6"
                TIME_SLOT_REF1="ts11" TIME_SLOT_REF2="ts12">
                <ANNOTATION_VALUE>cathy today we’re talking about a syndrome that sort of overlaps both of our specialties and that i find fascinating because of its pathophysiology</ANNOTATION_VALUE>
            </ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION>
        </ANNOTATION>
        <ANNOTATION>
            <ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION ANNOTATION_ID="a7"
                TIME_SLOT_REF1="ts13" TIME_SLOT_REF2="ts14">
                <ANNOTATION_VALUE>let’s get into it</ANNOTATION_VALUE>
            </ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION>
        </ANNOTATION>
        <ANNOTATION>
            <ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION ANNOTATION_ID="a8"
                TIME_SLOT_REF1="ts15" TIME_SLOT_REF2="ts16">
                <ANNOTATION_VALUE>well our patient is a thirty-eight-year-old previously healthy woman who presents from home critically ill with a high fever hypotension and mental disorientation</ANNOTATION_VALUE>
            </ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION>
        </ANNOTATION>
        <ANNOTATION>
            <ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION ANNOTATION_ID="a9"
                TIME_SLOT_REF1="ts17" TIME_SLOT_REF2="ts18">
                <ANNOTATION_VALUE>she remains hypotensive in the emergency department despite aggressive volume resuscitation and initiation of broad-spectrum antibiotics after blood cultures were drawn</ANNOTATION_VALUE>
            </ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION>
        </ANNOTATION>
        <ANNOTATION>
            <ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION ANNOTATION_ID="a10"
                TIME_SLOT_REF1="ts19" TIME_SLOT_REF2="ts20">
                <ANNOTATION_VALUE>she’s transferred to the medical intensive care unit where she’s intubated and mechanically ventilated for airway protection she’s administered continued fluid resuscitation</ANNOTATION_VALUE>
            </ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION>
        </ANNOTATION>
        <ANNOTATION>
            <ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION ANNOTATION_ID="a11"
                TIME_SLOT_REF1="ts21" TIME_SLOT_REF2="ts22">
                <ANNOTATION_VALUE>and because of persistent hypotension she’s started on norepinephrine a vasopressor</ANNOTATION_VALUE>
            </ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION>
        </ANNOTATION>
        <ANNOTATION>
            <ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION ANNOTATION_ID="a12"
                TIME_SLOT_REF1="ts23" TIME_SLOT_REF2="ts24">
                <ANNOTATION_VALUE>that this doesn’t sound good and there’s a wide differential of what could be going on tell me more about her medical history and symptoms leading up to this presentation</ANNOTATION_VALUE>
            </ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION>
        </ANNOTATION>
        <ANNOTATION>
            <ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION ANNOTATION_ID="a13"
                TIME_SLOT_REF1="ts25" TIME_SLOT_REF2="ts26">
                <ANNOTATION_VALUE>her spouse reports that she is healthy and on no medications she works as a rental-property manager she does not smoke or drink has no significant family history they do not have children by choice she gets an annual physical exam and there’s never been a problem</ANNOTATION_VALUE>
            </ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION>
        </ANNOTATION>
        <ANNOTATION>
            <ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION ANNOTATION_ID="a14"
                TIME_SLOT_REF1="ts27" TIME_SLOT_REF2="ts28">
                <ANNOTATION_VALUE>this illness started yesterday with her feeling febrile with malaise but no cough GI or GU symptoms her mental status worsened today prompting the spouse to call nine one one</ANNOTATION_VALUE>
            </ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION>
        </ANNOTATION>
        <ANNOTATION>
            <ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION ANNOTATION_ID="a15"
                TIME_SLOT_REF1="ts29" TIME_SLOT_REF2="ts30">
                <ANNOTATION_VALUE>and your physical examination?</ANNOTATION_VALUE>
            </ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION>
        </ANNOTATION>
        <ANNOTATION>
            <ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION ANNOTATION_ID="a16"
                TIME_SLOT_REF1="ts31" TIME_SLOT_REF2="ts32">
                <ANNOTATION_VALUE>on physical examination before intubation she was obtunded and not protecting her airway she was hypotensive but she had warm extremities nevertheless her oxygen saturation before intubation was normal</ANNOTATION_VALUE>
            </ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION>
        </ANNOTATION>
        <ANNOTATION>
            <ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION ANNOTATION_ID="a17"
                TIME_SLOT_REF1="ts33" TIME_SLOT_REF2="ts34">
                <ANNOTATION_VALUE>the only notable finding on physical examination is hepatomegaly and splenomegaly both by palpation and on POCUS</ANNOTATION_VALUE>
            </ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION>
        </ANNOTATION>
        <ANNOTATION>
            <ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION ANNOTATION_ID="a18"
                TIME_SLOT_REF1="ts35" TIME_SLOT_REF2="ts36">
                <ANNOTATION_VALUE>she has no skin rash petechiae or joint abnormalities also her neck is supple and not rigid</ANNOTATION_VALUE>
            </ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION>
        </ANNOTATION>
        <ANNOTATION>
            <ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION ANNOTATION_ID="a19"
                TIME_SLOT_REF1="ts37" TIME_SLOT_REF2="ts38">
                <ANNOTATION_VALUE>broad-spectrum antibiotics were appropriately started because of the fever the liver and spleen enlargement though does give me an idea tell me about her labs</ANNOTATION_VALUE>
            </ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION>
        </ANNOTATION>
        <ANNOTATION>
            <ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION ANNOTATION_ID="a20"
                TIME_SLOT_REF1="ts39" TIME_SLOT_REF2="ts40">
                <ANNOTATION_VALUE>on laboratory examination she has pancytopenia with reduced white-cell count platelets and hemoglobin her chemistries reveal a mild anion-gap acidosis with a borderline low glucose and a new doubling of her creatinine a blood gas on her current ventilatory settings shows a metabolic acidosis with respiratory compensation and adequate oxygenation on an FIO2 of zero point four zero and a PEEP of five</ANNOTATION_VALUE>
            </ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION>
        </ANNOTATION>
        <ANNOTATION>
            <ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION ANNOTATION_ID="a21"
                TIME_SLOT_REF1="ts41" TIME_SLOT_REF2="ts42">
                <ANNOTATION_VALUE>okay we’ve discussed peripheral blood smears recently and in this case with new pancytopenia that could be helpful did you do one</ANNOTATION_VALUE>
            </ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION>
        </ANNOTATION>
        <ANNOTATION>
            <ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION ANNOTATION_ID="a47"
                TIME_SLOT_REF1="ts43" TIME_SLOT_REF2="ts44">
                <ANNOTATION_VALUE>yep we did the peripheral blood smear confirms the lack of platelets and the white-cell count there are no schistocytes but there are a few bizarre large cells that appear to be macrophages ingesting red blood cells by looking around you see more cells that have ingested platelets and white cells</ANNOTATION_VALUE>
            </ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION>
        </ANNOTATION>
        <ANNOTATION>
            <ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION ANNOTATION_ID="a22"
                TIME_SLOT_REF1="ts45" TIME_SLOT_REF2="ts46">
                <ANNOTATION_VALUE>should we talk about the diagnosis or go to the question</ANNOTATION_VALUE>
            </ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION>
        </ANNOTATION>
        <ANNOTATION>
            <ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION ANNOTATION_ID="a23"
                TIME_SLOT_REF1="ts47" TIME_SLOT_REF2="ts48">
                <ANNOTATION_VALUE>let’s go right to the question the question asks in this patient all of the following would be expected to be increased except</ANNOTATION_VALUE>
            </ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION>
        </ANNOTATION>
        <ANNOTATION>
            <ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION ANNOTATION_ID="a24"
                TIME_SLOT_REF1="ts49" TIME_SLOT_REF2="ts50">
                <ANNOTATION_VALUE>option a is ADAMTS13</ANNOTATION_VALUE>
            </ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION>
        </ANNOTATION>
        <ANNOTATION>
            <ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION ANNOTATION_ID="a25"
                TIME_SLOT_REF1="ts51" TIME_SLOT_REF2="ts52">
                <ANNOTATION_VALUE>b d-dimer</ANNOTATION_VALUE>
            </ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION>
        </ANNOTATION>
        <ANNOTATION>
            <ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION ANNOTATION_ID="a26"
                TIME_SLOT_REF1="ts53" TIME_SLOT_REF2="ts54">
                <ANNOTATION_VALUE>c ferritin</ANNOTATION_VALUE>
            </ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION>
        </ANNOTATION>
        <ANNOTATION>
            <ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION ANNOTATION_ID="a27"
                TIME_SLOT_REF1="ts55" TIME_SLOT_REF2="ts56">
                <ANNOTATION_VALUE>d soluble IL-2 receptor</ANNOTATION_VALUE>
            </ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION>
        </ANNOTATION>
        <ANNOTATION>
            <ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION ANNOTATION_ID="a28"
                TIME_SLOT_REF1="ts57" TIME_SLOT_REF2="ts58">
                <ANNOTATION_VALUE>and e transaminases</ANNOTATION_VALUE>
            </ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION>
        </ANNOTATION>
        <ANNOTATION>
            <ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION ANNOTATION_ID="a29"
                TIME_SLOT_REF1="ts59" TIME_SLOT_REF2="ts60">
                <ANNOTATION_VALUE>well the key clinical findings in this case are its rapid acuity high fever CNS changes and hepatosplenomegaly sepsis still has to stay on the differential but when talking about the peripheral blood smear you described hemophagocytic cells the presence of those hemophagocytic cells on peripheral smear makes me think we are dealing with secondary hemophagocytic lymphohistiocytosis or HLH this is a grave diagnosis and her survival while not guaranteed relies on recognizing the syndrome and trying to treat her</ANNOTATION_VALUE>
            </ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION>
        </ANNOTATION>
        <ANNOTATION>
            <ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION ANNOTATION_ID="a30"
                TIME_SLOT_REF1="ts61" TIME_SLOT_REF2="ts62">
                <ANNOTATION_VALUE>tell me a little bit more about HLH before we get to the question</ANNOTATION_VALUE>
            </ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION>
        </ANNOTATION>
        <ANNOTATION>
            <ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION ANNOTATION_ID="a31"
                TIME_SLOT_REF1="ts63" TIME_SLOT_REF2="ts64">
                <ANNOTATION_VALUE>HLH is a condition of massive uncontrolled inflammation or hyperinflammation in adults it is often triggered by infections malignancies and autoimmune diseases HLH triggered by autoimmune conditions is also referred to as macrophage-activation syndrome the clinical picture of all forms of HLH is quite similar with the sepsis-like inflammation often leading to multiple-organ failure and death if not treated promptly and appropriately</ANNOTATION_VALUE>
            </ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION>
        </ANNOTATION>
        <ANNOTATION>
            <ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION ANNOTATION_ID="a32"
                TIME_SLOT_REF1="ts65" TIME_SLOT_REF2="ts66">
                <ANNOTATION_VALUE>you mentioned that you think our patient has secondary HLH that means there must be a primary form</ANNOTATION_VALUE>
            </ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION>
        </ANNOTATION>
        <ANNOTATION>
            <ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION ANNOTATION_ID="a33"
                TIME_SLOT_REF1="ts67" TIME_SLOT_REF2="ts68">
                <ANNOTATION_VALUE>yes the primary HLH syndromes are mendelian-inherited conditions with the most common form being familial HLH which is associated with lymphocyte-cytotoxicity defects it is typically seen in infants so that is why i said our patient likely has secondary HLH and talk a little bit more about the laboratory findings soluble IL-2 receptor and d-dimer are elevated ferritin and transaminases can also be elevated</ANNOTATION_VALUE>
            </ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION>
        </ANNOTATION>
        <ANNOTATION>
            <ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION ANNOTATION_ID="a34"
                TIME_SLOT_REF1="ts69" TIME_SLOT_REF2="ts70">
                <ANNOTATION_VALUE>particularly the ferritin is useful because you can get that back quickly and levels are typically over five hundred and often in the thousands</ANNOTATION_VALUE>
            </ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION>
        </ANNOTATION>
        <ANNOTATION>
            <ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION ANNOTATION_ID="a48"
                TIME_SLOT_REF1="ts71" TIME_SLOT_REF2="ts72">
                <ANNOTATION_VALUE>yes our patient’s ferritin came back at five thousand but not mentioned in your list is A ADAMTS13 so that’s not part of HLH</ANNOTATION_VALUE>
            </ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION>
        </ANNOTATION>
        <ANNOTATION>
            <ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION ANNOTATION_ID="a49"
                TIME_SLOT_REF1="ts73" TIME_SLOT_REF2="ts74">
                <ANNOTATION_VALUE>correct remember metalloprotease ADAMTS13 which cleaves von willebrand factor is relevant to TTP where it is low</ANNOTATION_VALUE>
            </ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION>
        </ANNOTATION>
        <ANNOTATION>
            <ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION ANNOTATION_ID="a35"
                TIME_SLOT_REF1="ts75" TIME_SLOT_REF2="ts76">
                <ANNOTATION_VALUE>okay so the answer to the question is A but let’s get back to HLH you mentioned a few potential triggers what are the most common</ANNOTATION_VALUE>
            </ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION>
        </ANNOTATION>
        <ANNOTATION>
            <ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION ANNOTATION_ID="a36"
                TIME_SLOT_REF1="ts77" TIME_SLOT_REF2="ts78">
                <ANNOTATION_VALUE>in adults infections were associated with fifty percent of HLH cases followed by neoplasms autoimmune diseases and transplants the most common associated infections were viral with EBV the most common followed by HIV among malignancies lymphomas were by far the most frequent and among autoimmune diseases systemic lupus erythematosus and adult-onset still’s disease were the most common but also relevant to our recent discussion of new immune-therapy regimens for cancer HLH can be associated with CAR-T therapy and immune-based therapies with the dramatic rise in these therapies it’s good we’re reviewing HLH</ANNOTATION_VALUE>
            </ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION>
        </ANNOTATION>
        <ANNOTATION>
            <ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION ANNOTATION_ID="a37"
                TIME_SLOT_REF1="ts79" TIME_SLOT_REF2="ts80">
                <ANNOTATION_VALUE>okay so the question relates to the diagnosis of HLH in this patient and you’ve already touched on a few of the lab abnormalities</ANNOTATION_VALUE>
            </ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION>
        </ANNOTATION>
        <ANNOTATION>
            <ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION ANNOTATION_ID="a38"
                TIME_SLOT_REF1="ts81" TIME_SLOT_REF2="ts82">
                <ANNOTATION_VALUE>so in contrast to primary HLH no exact or specific diagnostic test is available for secondary HLH a combination of clinical and laboratory criteria are often used called an hscore which is a weighted scoring system based on nine variables fever organomegaly known underlying immunosuppression cytopenias ferritin triglycerides fibrinogen AST and hemophagocytosis</ANNOTATION_VALUE>
            </ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION>
        </ANNOTATION>
        <ANNOTATION>
            <ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION ANNOTATION_ID="a39"
                TIME_SLOT_REF1="ts83" TIME_SLOT_REF2="ts84">
                <ANNOTATION_VALUE>having five of those the hscore has good diagnostic accuracy when evaluated in critically ill adults</ANNOTATION_VALUE>
            </ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION>
        </ANNOTATION>
        <ANNOTATION>
            <ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION ANNOTATION_ID="a40"
                TIME_SLOT_REF1="ts85" TIME_SLOT_REF2="ts86">
                <ANNOTATION_VALUE>okay well it sounds like our patient has it because she has fever organomegaly cytopenias hemophagocytosis and elevated ferritin so i assume we’ll send off viral studies in addition to those blood cultures</ANNOTATION_VALUE>
            </ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION>
        </ANNOTATION>
        <ANNOTATION>
            <ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION ANNOTATION_ID="a41"
                TIME_SLOT_REF1="ts87" TIME_SLOT_REF2="ts88">
                <ANNOTATION_VALUE>yes definitely need to continue with the infectious workup for this patient</ANNOTATION_VALUE>
            </ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION>
        </ANNOTATION>
        <ANNOTATION>
            <ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION ANNOTATION_ID="a42"
                TIME_SLOT_REF1="ts89" TIME_SLOT_REF2="ts90">
                <ANNOTATION_VALUE>okay so the teaching points of this case are that hemophagocytic lymphohistiocytosis or HLH is a syndromic disease characterized by hyperacute inflammation and activated histiocytes it can present just like sepsis but will also have findings of a high ferritin organomegaly and often hemophagocytosis most cases are presumed to be a reaction to a viral infection or an occult malignancy</ANNOTATION_VALUE>
            </ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION>
        </ANNOTATION>
        <ANNOTATION>
            <ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION ANNOTATION_ID="a43"
                TIME_SLOT_REF1="ts91" TIME_SLOT_REF2="ts92">
                <ANNOTATION_VALUE>with the growing use of new cell-based therapies the incidence of HLH may be on the rise</ANNOTATION_VALUE>
            </ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION>
        </ANNOTATION>
        <ANNOTATION>
            <ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION ANNOTATION_ID="a45"
                TIME_SLOT_REF1="ts93" TIME_SLOT_REF2="ts94">
                <ANNOTATION_VALUE>visit the show notes for links to helpful resources including related chapters and review questions from harrison’s available exclusively on accessmedicine</ANNOTATION_VALUE>
            </ALIGNABLE_ANNOTATION>
        </ANNOTATION>
